    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna 172 and saw stuff about the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed? and why is it such a big deal if it gets blocked up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pitot tube measures airspeed by comparing the pressure of the air flowing into it with the ambient air pressure. When air flows into the tube, it creates a difference in pressure, which is then converted into an electrical signal that is used to calculate airspeed. If the pitot tube gets blocked, it stops measuring airspeed accurately, which can be dangerous during flight. This is because the pilot relies on this data to maintain a safe airspeed. A blocked pitot tube can cause the aircraft to lose the crucial information needed to fly safely, leading to potential accidents. It's crucial to ensure the pitot tube is clean and unobstructed to maintain reliable airspeed readings.",
      "source": "target",
